<p>
<seg id=1> All listeners please take a look at the situation in China as follows. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=2> Days ago the Chinese Government arrested several dissidents in order to prevent some Chinese Democratic Members from gathering together in Zhejing province in Shanghai. </seg>
<seg id=3> Please listen to the report by the Chinese Department of the Voice of America, as announced by Yue Qing. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> According to news from the Chinese Human Rights Information Center, Hangzhou city public security personnel took away two Chinese Democratic members, Zhenmin Zhu and Qinxiang Mao from their homes on Friday afternoon. </seg>
<seg id=5> At the present time nobody know where they are. </seg>
<seg id=6> Before this happened police already arrested four Democratic Party leaders.  They are Zhengxian Yao, Guotao Li, Yirong Wu, Rongqin Wang. </seg>
<seg id=7> The news from the Chinese Human Rights Information Center said that originally about twenty members of the Chinese Democratic Party from Shanghai branch had planned to hold their first meeting in a restaurant in Hangzhou city on Friday afternoon. </seg>
<seg id=8> Police started making arrests after they learned of the planned meeting. </seg>
<seg id=9> Additionally, the public security personnel in different cities of Zhejiang province warned the rest of the Democratic Members not to leave their homes or they would be arrested also. </seg>
<seg id=10> The Chinese Government regards the Chinese Democratic Party as an illegal organization, and has already arrested and tried some supporters and members of this organization. </seg>
<seg id=11> However, in most cases the people are released soon after their arrests. </seg>
<seg id=12> The Associated Press, Reuters and AFP all have reported the newest situation announced by the Chinese Human Rights Information Center. </seg>
</p>
